\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 to the real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 In this paper, we will only consider 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 sets of events: we therefore restrict our attention to non-empty finite
 sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 as the sample space.
 The space of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 includes every possible subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

: it is the powerset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $2^{\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 Given the set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default
 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas:\events\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\Omega)=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 of pairwise disjoint events, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\bigcup_{i}E_{i})=\tensor*[_{\mathbb{R}}]{\sum}{_{i}}\pmeas(E_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tensor*[_{\mathbb{R}}]{\sum}{_{i}}\pmeas(E_{i})$
\end_inset

