\begin_layout Subsection
Measuring Probabilities: Buffon's Needle Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Measuring-Probabilities:-Buffon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous section, the probability of each event is known a priori.
 In reality, we seldom know much about events, but we could still assume
 each event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has a probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

.
 If we want to know the probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

, we could run 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 independent trials.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote whether the event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 occurs in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th trial or not, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 could be approximated to given accuracy by the relative frequency
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the probability converging to one as 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity.
 This fact is called the law of large numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bernoulli2006,Kolmogorov1950,Uspensky1937,Shafer1976,544199"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we drop a needle of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 onto a floor made of equally spaced parallel lines a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 apart.
 It is a known fact that the probability of the needle crossing a line is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buffon1777,DeMorgan1872,Hall1873,Uspensky1937"

\end_inset

.
 We analyze this situation in the mathematical framework of probability
 spaces paying special attention to the resources needed to estimate the
 probability computationally or experimentally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formalize the experiment, we consider an experimental setup consisting
 of a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 identical needles of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 We throw the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 needles one needle at a time, and observe the number 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of needles that cross a line.
 The sample space can be expressed as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X,-\}^{N}$
\end_inset

 of sequences of characters of length 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 where each character is either 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to indicate a needle crossing a line or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 to indicate a needle not crossing a line.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

, the probability of the event that exactly 2 needles cross lines
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\{-XX,X{-}X,XX-\}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated by the relative frequency
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Generally, the probability of the event that exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 needles out of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 total needles cross lines can be estimated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{M}{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an actual experiment with 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.75$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hall1873"

\end_inset

, it was found that 
\begin_inset Formula $236$
\end_inset

 crossed a line so the relative frequency is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.472$
\end_inset

 whereas the idealized mathematical probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.4774\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 In a larger experiment with 
\begin_inset Formula $5000$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.8$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Uspensky1937"

\end_inset

, the relative frequency was calculated to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5064$
\end_inset

 whereas the idealized mathematical probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5092\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 We see that the observed probability approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

 but only if 
\emph on
larger and larger resources
\emph default
 are expended.
 These resource considerations suggest that it is possible to replace the
 real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with rational numbers up to a certain precision related to the particular
 experiment in question.
 There is clearly a connection between the number of needles and the achievable
 precision: in the hypothetical experiment with 3 needles, it is not sensible
 to retain 100 digits in the expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is however another more subtle assumption of unbounded computational
 power in the experiment.
 We are assuming that we can always determine with certainty whether a needle
 is crossing a line.
 But 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lines
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the the floor have thickness, their distance apart is not exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and the needles lengths are not all absolutely equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 These perturbations make the events 
