\begin_inset Formula $[l_{1},r_{1}]$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that another disjoint event 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 has interval probability 
\begin_inset Formula $[l_{2},r_{2}]$
\end_inset

, what is the interval probability of the event 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\cup E_{2}$
\end_inset

? The answer is somewhat subtle: although it is possible to use the sum
 of the intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $[l_{1}+l_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]$
\end_inset

 as the combined probability, one can do find a much tighter interval if
 information 
\emph on
against
\emph default
 the event (i.e., information about the complement event) is also taken into
 consideration.
 Formally, for a general event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $[l,r]$
\end_inset

, the evidence that contradicts 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an evidence supporting the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

