\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Probability Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, there are many possible probability measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\events\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 The Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born1983,Mermin2007,RiederSvozil2007"

\end_inset

, a postulate of quantum mechanics, states that each pure quantum state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

 induces a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{\phi}(E)=\ip{\phi}{E\phi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the Born rule can be extended to a mixed state.
 Suppose we want to prepare a quantum system.
 As we discussed in classical probability, our ability of preparing a state
 might not be prefect.
 If we want to prepare 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

, we may turn out preparing a set of state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 each with probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

, then the state of the system can be expressed as a density matrix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sum_{j}q_{j}\proj{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is natural that the quantum probability measure introduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 with respect to probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "peres1995quantum,544199,RiederSvozil2007"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mu_{\rho}\left(E\right) & = & \Tr\left(\rho E\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}\mu_{\phi_{j}}\left(E\right)\textrm{ .}\label{BornRule.mixed}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, Gleason's theorem states that given a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, there exist a mixed state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that induces such a measure using the Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

.
 The theorem is only valid in Hilbert spaces with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq3$
